04695nam a22006495i 9780271083056DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710830567 a10.1515/97802710830562doi  a(DE-B1597)583865  a(OCoLC)1269268905  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0150702bisacsh04a709.4022231 aProctor-Tiffany, Mariah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMedieval Art in Motion :bThe Inventory and Gift Giving of Queen Clémence de Hongrie /cMariah Proctor-Tiffany. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b28 color/30 b&w illustrations/5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Terminology and Nomenclature -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Life, Times, and Art of an International Queen -- t2 Systems of Exchange: Moving Art and Material Culture -- t3 The Body, the Altar, and the Table: Possessions and Sites of Identity Proclamation -- t4 The Queen's Manuscripts and Identity -- t5 Gift Giving in the Gothic World -- t6 The Queen and Ritual Gift Giving -- t7 Gifts to Individuals, Near and Far -- tConclusion: Good and Glorious Exchange -- tAppendix 1 The Testament of Clémence de Hongrie -- tAppendix 2 The Inventory of Clémence de Hongrie -- tAppendix 3 Glossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this visually rich volume, Mariah Proctor-Tiffany reconstructs the art collection and material culture of the fourteenth-century French queen Clémence de Hongrie, illuminating the way the royal widow gave objects as part of a deliberate strategy to create a lasting legacy for herself and her family in medieval Paris.After the sudden death of her husband, King Louis X, and the loss of her promised income, young Clémence fought for her high social status by harnessing the visual power of possessions, displaying them, and offering her luxurious objects as gifts. Clémence adeptly performed the role of queen, making a powerful argument for her place at court and her income as she adorned her body, the altars of her chapels, and her dining tables with sculptures, paintings, extravagant textiles, manuscripts, and jewelry-the exclusive accoutrements of royalty. Proctor-Tiffany analyzes the queen's collection, maps the geographic trajectories of her gifts of art, and interprets Clémence's generosity using anthropological theories of exchange and gift giving. Engaging with the art inventory of a medieval French woman, this lavishly illustrated microhistory sheds light on the material and social culture of the late Middle Ages. Scholars and students of medieval art, women's studies, digital mapping, and the anthropology of ritual and gift giving especially will welcome Proctor-Tiffany's meticulous research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArt patronagezFrancezParisxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aArtxCollectors and collectingzFrancezParisxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aArt, MedievalzFrancezParis. 0aGiftszFrancexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aART / History / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271083056zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271083056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271083056/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-all